73","1350":"1350","Abt 1406":"circa 1406","Abt 1404":"circa 1404","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1387":"1387","about 1402":"circa 1402","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","about 1400":"circa 1400","1409":"1409","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","Of, Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England","Shelfanger, Norfolk, England":"Shelfanger, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1387–1406":"1387–1406","1373–1409":"1373–1409","1402–1415":"1402–1415","1404–1415":"1404–1415","1406–1420":"1406–1420","1406–1464":"1406–1464","1349–Male":"1349–Deceased","1350–1407":"1350–1407","1373":"1373","1350":"1350","Abt 1406":"about 1406","Abt 1404":"about 1404","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1387":"1387","about 1402":"about 1402","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","about 1400":"about 1400","1409":"1409","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","Of, Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England","Shelfanger, Norfolk, England":"Shelfanger, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Noone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Malachy, Kieran, Peadar.","Irish (Galway): variant of   Noon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Noon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish (Connacht): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Nuadháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nuadhán</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>Nuadha</i>, the name of an ancient Celtic god.","English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>none</i>, Middle Dutch <i>noene</i> ‘noon’, the time of brightest sunshine, hence perhaps a nickname for a bright and cheerful person or for someone born at that time of day. The word is derived from Latin <i>nona (hora)</i> ‘ninth (hour)’, i.e. about three o’clock. The change in meaning of the vocabulary word from mid afternoon to midday, probably occurred as a result of monastic meal times being brought forward."]},{"name":"Nooney","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Noone  ."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Anna Noone was born in 1387, in Saxlingham, Norfolk, England, her father, Edmund Noon, was 39 and her mother, Isabel Visdelou, was 37. She married Sir John Bernak I about 1400, in Saxlingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1406, in Shelfanger, Norfolk, England, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1387–1406":"1387–1406","1373–1409":"1373–1409","1402–1415":"1402–1415","1404–1415":"1404–1415","1406–1420":"1406–1420","1406–1464":"1406–1464","1349–Male":"1349–Surnud","1350–1407":"1350–1407","1373":"1373","1350":"1350","Abt 1406":"umbes 1406","Abt 1404":"umbes 1404","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1387":"1387","about 1402":"umbes 1402","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1409":"1409","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","Of, Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England","Shelfanger, Norfolk, England":"Shelfanger, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1387